The paper focuses on automatic speaker verification technology and its vulnerability to spoofing attacks, specifically text-to-speech and voice conversion techniques. This suggests a focus on signal processing and machine learning techniques for speech analysis and classification, which are commonly found in the sub-categories of cs.SD (sound and music computing) and cs.CL (computation and language). The paper also discusses the performance of different feature sets and back-end models, indicating a focus on machine learning and statistical analysis, which are commonly found in the sub-categories of cs.SI (social and information networks), cs.CR (cryptography and security), and cs.LG (machine learning).
